  "texts": [
    "From h[R i (x)] ⊆ X ′, we have int(cl(⇓h[R i (x)])) ⊆ int(cl(⇓X ′)), and from X ′ ∈ P ′ ⊆ RO(S ′, ⊑ ′), we have X ′ = int(cl(⇓X ′)), so int(cl(⇓h[R i (x)])) ⊆ X ′.",
    "Then since R ′ i (h(x)) ⊆ int(cl(⇓R ′ i (h(x)))), we have R ′ i (h(x)) ⊆ X ′ by B3.For part 5, we assume that for anyX ′ ∈ P ′, h[R i (x)] ⊆ X ′ implies R ′ i (h(x)) ⊆ X ′.",
    "By Fact 2.17.2, h[R i (x)] ⊆ int(cl(⇓h[R i (x)])) ∈ RO(S ′, ⊑ ′), so since F ′ is full, we have int(cl(⇓h[R i (x)])) ∈ P ′, so we can use our pre- vious assumption with X ′ = int(cl(⇓h[R i (x)])) to conclude that R ′ i (h(x)) ⊆ int(cl(⇓h[R i (x)])), which implies that int(cl(⇓R ′ i (h(x)))) ⊆ int(cl(⇓h[R i (x)])), which is B3.Thus, p-morphisms use B1 and strict possibility morphisms use B2.",
    "We could also give a special name to morphisms satisfying B3, but we will not need to in this paper.An analysis similar to that of the back conditions for R i above applies to back conditions for ⊑.",
